---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import HomelabBand from '~/components/homelab/HomelabBand.astro';
import EurocraftByline from '~/components/homelab/EurocraftByline.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '~/components/Breadcrumb.astro';
import RoofCalculator from '~/components/homelab/RoofCalculator.tsx';
import AdSlot from '~/components/ads/AdSlot.tsx';
import { COST_ENGINE_UPDATED } from '~/lib/homelab/roof-cost-engine';

const title = 'Roof Replacement Cost Calculator (2026) — Reviewed by a Texas GC | Kefiw';
const description = 'Range-based roof replacement cost calculator: enter sqft, material, pitch, stories, tear-off, decking risk, complexity, permit, warranty. Get low/typical/high estimate, $/sqft, financing payment, and questions to ask each roofer.';

const webApp = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebApplication',
  name: 'Roof Replacement Cost Calculator',
  description,
  applicationCategory: 'BusinessApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'Any',
  url: new URL('/homelab/roof-replacement-cost-calculator/', Astro.site).toString(),
  offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'USD' },
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonical="/homelab/roof-replacement-cost-calculator/"
  keywords={["roof replacement cost calculator","roof cost estimator","roof cost per square foot","metal vs asphalt roof cost"]}
>
  <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" slot="head" set:html={JSON.stringify(webApp)} />
  <HomelabBand active="calculator" />
  <Breadcrumb crumbs={[
    { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
    { href: '/homelab/', label: 'Property Improve' },
    { href: '/homelab/roof-replacement-cost-calculator/', label: 'Roof Replacement Cost Calculator' },
  ]} />
  <article class="container-wide py-6">
    <header class="mb-4">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Roof Replacement Cost Calculator</h1>
      <p class="mt-2 max-w-3xl text-slate-700">
        Get a range-based estimate for a full roof replacement — material, labor, tear-off, decking-rot risk, permit and warranty included.
        Reviewed by a working Texas-licensed general contractor. No lead capture, no fake precision.
      </p>
    </header>

    <EurocraftByline updated={COST_ENGINE_UPDATED} />

    <div class="my-4">
      <AdSlot client:idle zoneId="ALPHA" />
    </div>

    <section aria-label="Calculator" class="mb-8">
      <RoofCalculator client:load />
    </section>

    <div class="my-6">
      <AdSlot client:idle zoneId="GAMMA" />
    </div>

    <section class="prose-tool max-w-3xl">
      <h2>How to use this calculator</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Pick area input.</strong> "Home sqft" estimates roof area from your floor plan and pitch. "Roof sqft" is more accurate if you have a measurement report.</li>
        <li><strong>Be honest about pitch and complexity.</strong> A 3-gable suburban hip is "standard hip"; a Victorian with three dormers and a turret is "cut-up."</li>
        <li><strong>Tear-off layers.</strong> If you don't know, count from the eave: 1 layer is most common; 2 layers means a previous "lay-over" install (legal in some jurisdictions, banned in others).</li>
        <li><strong>Decking risk.</strong> Older roofs (20+ years) and any history of leaks bump this to "medium" or "high." This is the line item most calculators hide.</li>
        <li><strong>Test one cost-saving strategy at a time.</strong> Roof-over, owner-supplied materials, installer-only labor, selective flashing reuse, and trimming upsells are different risks. Do not blend them into one vague cheap bid.</li>
        <li><strong>Compare against bids.</strong> If three bids land inside this range, pick on workmanship and warranty — not price. If one is well below, ask what's missing from the scope.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Real ways to reduce the roof cost</h2>
      <p>
        The calculator now includes a cost-saving strategy selector because "new roof cost" is not one decision.
        A full contractor scope is the baseline. A roof-over, owner-supplied material order, installer-only crew,
        selective flashing reuse, or trimmed warranty/upgrade package can lower the first invoice, but each moves
        risk to a different place.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Roof-over:</strong> can save tear-off and dump fees, but only when code allows it and the existing roof is flat, dry, one layer, and structurally sound.</li>
        <li><strong>Buy materials yourself:</strong> can pressure markup, but you own shortages, damaged bundles, wrong SKUs, color-lot mismatch, returns, and sometimes warranty conflict.</li>
        <li><strong>Installer-only labor:</strong> can be cheapest, but the contract must name insurance, permit, dry-in, cleanup, lien waivers, and who owns leaks.</li>
        <li><strong>Selective flashing reuse:</strong> pipe boots and damaged metal are usually cheap to replace; buried step or counterflashing may be reused if it is sound and correctly lapped.</li>
        <li><strong>Trim upsells:</strong> separate gutters, premium shingles, warranty packages, vague ventilation work, and cosmetic trim from the base roof.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        More detail: <a href="/guides/save-on-roof-replacement-cost/">How to save on roof replacement cost</a>,
        <a href="/guides/roof-over-vs-tear-off/"> roof-over vs tear-off</a>, and
        <a href="/guides/buy-roofing-materials-yourself/"> buying roofing materials yourself</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Items to handle while roofers are already up there</h2>
      <p>
        Roof replacement is the cheap-access moment. You already have ladders, tear-off, dry-in, and crews on site.
        Before final scope, walk the roof accessories and nearby trees with photos.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Pipe boots and vent flashings:</strong> replace brittle rubber collars and cracked boots instead of burying them under new shingles.</li>
        <li><strong>Chimney cap, chase cover, flue cap, storm collar, and visible flue corrosion:</strong> separate masonry/flue safety from roofing scope, but do not ignore a failing cap while access is easy.</li>
        <li><strong>Chimney flashing:</strong> price step flashing, counterflashing, back pan, cricket, and kick-out flashing separately. Replace failed metal; reuse sound buried counterflashing only if everyone agrees in writing.</li>
        <li><strong>Skylights and curbs:</strong> older skylights often deserve new flashing kits or replacement before new shingles lock them in.</li>
        <li><strong>Vents and ventilation:</strong> verify ridge/off-ridge vents, intake, bath/kitchen exhaust routing, and wind/rain-rated vents in storm zones.</li>
        <li><strong>Decking, fascia, soffit, and gutter edge:</strong> decide per-sheet decking price and edge wood repair before tear-off surprises become change-order pressure.</li>
        <li><strong>Trees touching the roof:</strong> branches rubbing shingles remove granules, hold moisture, feed algae, clog valleys, and create a maintenance argument for future insurance claims. Trim before the new roof goes on.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Insurance discounts: hail rating, wind rating, and paperwork</h2>
      <p>
        Hail-resistant shingles and wind-mitigation roof work are different things. Class 3 or Class 4 impact resistance
        can help with hail credits if your carrier recognizes the product. Windstorm discounts or eligibility may depend on
        installed details: nailing, deck attachment, sealed deck, edges, vents, and certification.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Two layers, not three:</strong> in many code-based reroof rules, one existing asphalt layer may be recoverable; two existing layers means tear-off. Do not create a third layer.</li>
        <li><strong>Impact form:</strong> in Texas/TWIA contexts, ask for TDI Form PC068 after installation for impact-resistant roofing documentation. Private carriers may use their own form.</li>
        <li><strong>Class 3 / Class 4 proof:</strong> collect packaging photos showing UL 2218 classification, manufacturer, year, and product brand before the packaging leaves the site.</li>
        <li><strong>Shingle nailing:</strong> ask whether the manufacturer high-wind installation requires six nails per shingle and require photos of the package instructions and installed pattern.</li>
        <li><strong>Roof deck nailing:</strong> for FORTIFIED-style re-roofs, IBHS guidance calls for 8d ring-shank nails at 6 inches on center, and 4 inches on center at gable ends, with photo documentation.</li>
        <li><strong>Windstorm certification:</strong> coastal Texas work may need WPI-8 or WPI-8E windstorm documentation for TWIA/windstorm coverage eligibility.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        More detail: <a href="/guides/roof-hail-wind-insurance-discounts/">Roof hail and wind insurance discounts</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What a good roofing quote includes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Tear-off and disposal scope, by layer count</li>
        <li>Decking replacement contingency — per-sheet price spelled out</li>
        <li>Underlayment type (synthetic vs felt) and ice/water shield coverage</li>
        <li>Starter strips and ridge cap (specialty pieces, not field shingles)</li>
        <li>Flashing scope at every penetration and transition: replace, reuse, or repair-in-place with reasons</li>
        <li>Tree-limb rub inspection and branch trimming plan before new shingles are installed</li>
        <li>Class 3 / Class 4 impact-resistant paperwork if you expect an insurance discount</li>
        <li>High-wind nailing pattern and deck-attachment documentation where discounts or windstorm certification depend on it</li>
        <li>Drip edge install, ridge vent or other ventilation</li>
        <li>Workmanship warranty length + transferability</li>
        <li>Manufacturer warranty registered in your name (system warranties require this)</li>
        <li>Permit pulled by the contractor, not by you as homeowner</li>
        <li>Certificate of insurance + active state contractor license</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Common roof-cost myths</h2>
      <h3>"My neighbor paid $X, so mine should too."</h3>
      <p>
        Neighbor's roof has different pitch, different penetrations, possibly different decking condition.
        Within the same neighborhood we routinely see 30–40% spread on legitimate, well-scoped bids.
      </p>
      <h3>"The cheapest bid wins."</h3>
      <p>
        The cheapest bid is usually the one missing scope. Common omissions: drip edge, starter strip,
        flashing replacement, decking allowance, debris removal, and permit. A bid that quotes square
        footage and one shingle SKU is not a complete quote.
      </p>
      <h3>"Never roof over old shingles."</h3>
      <p>
        A roof-over can be legitimate on the right house, but it is not a magic discount. It needs code permission,
        one existing layer, flat shingles, no active leaks, no sagging, and a sound deck. If those facts are not
        checked, tear-off is buying information, not just labor.
      </p>
      <h3>"Always replace all flashing."</h3>
      <p>
        Replace cheap failed pieces such as pipe boots, rusted valley metal, and damaged drip edge. But step
        flashing or counterflashing buried behind siding, stucco, brick, or stone should be discussed separately.
        Sometimes reuse is rational; sometimes it is the future leak. A good quote names each decision.
      </p>
      <h3>"Insurance will pay for everything."</h3>
      <p>
        Insurance pays scope they approve, minus deductible, minus depreciation hold-back until work
        is verified complete. <strong>Code upgrades</strong> (e.g., synthetic underlayment now required
        by code) and <strong>betterment items</strong> (you choose architectural over 3-tab) come out of pocket.
      </p>

      <h2>Insurance claim notes</h2>
      <p>
        If your area took hail or wind in the last 12 months, file a claim before doing anything else.
        Adjusters look for granular loss, lifted shingles, soft spots from impact, and bruised mat. They
        will measure, photograph, and produce a scope. Common terms to know:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>RCV vs ACV.</strong> Replacement Cost Value pays full like-kind-and-quality. Actual Cash Value subtracts depreciation. Most modern policies are RCV but pay ACV first and release the depreciation after work completes.</li>
        <li><strong>Code-upgrade endorsement.</strong> Pays the difference between old code and current code (drip edge, ice/water shield, decking spacing). Often optional — check your policy.</li>
        <li><strong>Supplements.</strong> Items the contractor finds on tear-off that weren't in the original scope (rotted decking, additional flashing). Submit before installing.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>About this calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Cost data is set by Eurocraft (Texas-licensed general contractor) and reflects mid-2026 South-region pricing.
        Numbers are reviewed quarterly. See <a href="/homelab/methodology/">methodology</a> for inputs and assumptions,
        and <a href="/homelab/about/">about</a> for editorial credentials.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="my-6">
      <AdSlot client:idle zoneId="DELTA" format="multiplex" />
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
